comment_text: Training the imagination in meditation isn’t awakening. It’s a form of hypnotism. You’re not waking up, you’re going under. Visualization, guided fantasies, manifestation. It’s all self-hypnosis dressed up as some sort of pseudo-spirituality. Fake feelings, fake visions, fake wisdom. And underneath is the biggest con of all-->non-duality, the lie that you and God are the same. Feels good, but that’s not awareness. That’s ego dreaming, playing God. True consciousness is when you stop manufacturing images and thoughts and come to see reality as it is. The ‘most advanced’ meditation is the simplest. It’s non-contemplative. No mantras, no visualizations, no training thoughts. Just awareness as it is, nothing added. That’s how you get free of negative emotions, not by fantasizing and thinking them away. Willfully 'downregulating' brain chemistry manipulating physiology is not the answer. It just feels like it is.

I found it to be a tedious exercise of practicing "being still," remaining in the present moment by closing one's eyes until a distracting thought would pull you away. FWIW....Quantum = sub atomic and does weird stuff (but definable stuff). zero loss energy exchange, entanglement, etc. Can't be measured but can be observed (with difficulty. And the fields are probabilistic functions of small individual related-but-not-connected-sub atomic parts (think light waves and photons). Lots of cool speculative science re consciousness and other biological systems (a few confirmed / accepted bio quantum discoveries - like photosynthesis) 

Look - there's a lot of eastern medicine and practices that are super beneficial and not yet understood (re: meditation), western med and science is super fixated on measuring a thing for it to be real, vice observing in the system as a whole. But the hairs stand up when someone with Dr in front of their name defines science in a way that’s...not scientific. comment_text:
Natuurlijk! Hier is in het kort de meditatie-aanpak van Dr. Joe Dispenza om stress snel uit te schakelen:

1. Stop en word je bewust

Zodra je merkt dat je gestrest bent, pauzeer even.

Herken welke gedachten en gevoelens je op dat moment hebt.


2. Ademhaling gebruiken

Haal langzaam en diep adem (bijv. 5 seconden in, 5 seconden uit).

Richt je aandacht op je hart of je borststreek in plaats van op je hoofd.

Dit verlaagt direct de stressrespons in je lichaam.


3. Verplaats je aandacht

In plaats van te focussen op het probleem of de stressbron, richt je je op een positief gevoel (bijv. dankbaarheid, kalmte, liefde).

Het idee is dat je hersenen en lichaam dan een nieuw signaal krijgen dat je veilig bent.


4. Creëer een nieuwe staat van zijn

Zie en voel jezelf al in de toestand die je wél wilt (rustig, vrij, dankbaar).

Door dit regelmatig te oefenen, programmeer je je brein en zenuwstelsel om sneller uit stress te schakelen.


Dr. Dispenza benadrukt dat je met oefening letterlijk je brein en lichaam kunt hertrainen, zodat ze automatisch van stress naar kalmte overschakelen.

Perfect! Hier is een korte stap-voor-stap oefening geïnspireerd op Dr. Joe Dispenza die je meteen kunt toepassen wanneer je stress voelt
---

🧘‍♀️ Mini-oefening om stress uit te zetten

Stap 1 – Stop & merk op (10 sec)
Sluit je ogen (als dat kan) en zeg in jezelf: “Ik merk dat ik stress ervaar.”
Alleen al het opmerken haalt je uit de automatische stressreactie.

Stap 2 – Adem rustig (1 min)

Adem 4 seconden in door je neus.

Houd 2 seconden vast.

Adem 6 seconden uit door je mond.

Herhaal dit rustig 5 keer.


Stap 3 – Breng je aandacht naar je hart (30 sec)
Leg je hand op je borst. Stel je voor dat je adem in en uit je hart stroomt.

Stap 4 – Activeer een positief gevoel (1–2 min)
Denk aan iets waar je dankbaar voor bent of iemand die je een goed gevoel geeft.
Probeer dit gevoel écht te voelen in je hartstreek.

Stap 5 – Creëer je nieuwe staat (30 sec)
Zie jezelf nu in een rustige, sterke en heldere staat van zijn.
Zeg zachtjes in jezelf: “Dit is wie ik ben.”


---

✨ Als je dit een paar minuten doet, schakelt je zenuwstelsel over van stress (overlevingsmodus) naar kalmte en herstel (creatiemodus).

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
I agree with Dr Joe's assessment that people can heal from psychologically induced illness using meditation.
But it can take time to cultivate a  meditation practice.
His speaking skills have improved significantly.
I had bought a recording of one of his  retreats from his web site in 2017 that contained lecture and guided meditations.  The guided meditations weren't helpful to me.

I wasn't willing to go to one of his retreats in Mexico to experience the meditations first hand after hearing that recording.
 
Instead, I took some online somatic meditation and Tibetan buddhist sutrayana and meditation courses from a long time teacher, which were great.
I added chanting Om and kept practicing the Tibetan meditation (shamatha, vipashyana, tonglen, maitri) plus gratitude practice and journaling to my daily practice.
I practiced an hour a day at 4am each day.  On weekend days, I practiced 2-4 hours.  It took over a year of dedicated practice before I was able to become adept at applying my practice in everyday life.
Once I began the practicing off the cushion and on the cushion each day, my life really began to change.

I think Dr Joe is a smart guy and he's right.  I'm glad he's helping to heal people, but I don't regret taking the Buddhist courses.
I was healed.
My courses had sangha discussions and group meditations.
We discussed books written by the teacher.
We wrote our experiences in a blog for each book we read.
It was in a sangha discussion that I experienced a breakthrough.
It brought on tremendous turmoil initially, but it was great to help me deal with past trauma.
What's more, years have passed since then without regression.

Afterward, I went to another set of Tibetan buddhist online courses that included meditation.
That was another excellent set of courses.
It was great to heal from stress-related illness without going to a western doctor.

His perspective on moving beyond just analyzing the past and actively creating a new future in the present moment sounds like a really valuable approach to personal growth.

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
People, yes I want to believe this too but remember... Once Dr OZ and Dr Phil were also revered. When these new gurus come along ALWAYS investigate and look into what their critics say about them. Below is a brief assessment of things I could find. This guy mixes known good science like "yes meditation is good for you" and mixes it with a healthy dose of quantum mechanics' metaphysical bullshit. I really love the DOAC podcast but it irks me when guests like this are booked as it gives them a platform to spew their nonsense. I get the guy is hugely popular, but Steven please delve deeper and ask pointed counter questions to see if their assertions stand up to the scientific method. 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Dr. Joe Dispenza's teachings, while popular, have attracted skepticism from various quarters. Here’s an overview of the main critiques:

**1. Misuse of Scientific Terminology**

Critics argue that Dispenza employs complex scientific terms—like "quantum physics" and "neuroplasticity"—in ways that lack proper context or accuracy. This can give an impression of scientific legitimacy without substantial evidence.

> "He uses terms such as 'quantum' and 'neuroplasticity' without proper context, leading to misunderstandings about these scientific concepts." 

**2. Lack of Empirical Evidence**

Many of Dispenza's claims, especially those suggesting that meditation and positive thinking can lead to spontaneous physical healings, are criticized for lacking rigorous scientific validation.

> "His assertions about self-healing through thought alone are not supported by substantial clinical research."

**3. Overemphasis on Personal Responsibility**

Some detractors believe that Dispenza's teachings may inadvertently suggest that individuals are entirely responsible for their health conditions, potentially leading to feelings of guilt or neglect of necessary medical treatments.

> "His philosophy might imply that failure to heal oneself is due to inadequate mental effort, which is a problematic stance." 

**4. Commercialization Concerns**

The high cost of Dispenza's workshops and retreats has raised eyebrows, with some questioning whether financial gain is a significant motivator behind his offerings.

> "Critics have raised concerns about the high cost of attending Dr. Dispenza's workshops and events, suggesting that it may prioritize commercial interests over genuine spiritual or personal development." 

**5. Potential for Exaggerated Claims**

Skeptics caution that some of Dispenza's narratives and testimonials may be embellished, lacking the scientific backing necessary to substantiate such claims.

> "Some individuals feel that the transformation stories and claims presented in his books and seminars may be exaggerated or anecdotal, lacking sufficient scientific validation." 

**Notable Critics and Their Perspectives**

- **Clarke van Steenderen**: In an article for the *Skeptical Inquirer*, van Steenderen critiques Dispenza's book *Becoming Supernatural*, highlighting concerns about the misuse of scientific terms and the presentation of unverified claims as facts.

- **Marc Siegel**: Writing for *Slate*, Siegel acknowledges that while the documentary *Heal*, featuring Dispenza, makes some valid points about positivity, it lacks critical caveats and may overpromise on the benefits of mind-body interventions.

- **Edzard Ernst**: A former professor of complementary medicine, Ernst has labeled Dispenza's teachings as pseudoscientific, emphasizing the absence of credible scientific evidence supporting his methods. 

**Further Reading and Resources**

For a more in-depth exploration of these critiques, you might find the following articles informative:

- [Joe Dispenza's Becoming Supernatural: How Common People Are Being Misled](https://skepticalinquirer.org/2020/06/joe-dispenzas-becoming-supernatural-how-common-people-are-being-misled/)

- [Meditation is big business. The science isn't so clear.](https://www.asbmb.org/asbmb-today/science/010724/meditation-is-big-business-the-science-isn-t-so-cl)

- [How Joseph Dispenza Seduced America With Pseudoscience](https://www.thedailybeast.com/how-joseph-dispenza-seduced-america-with-pseudoscience/)

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
To go through life nowadays is like skiing downhill—you’re too nervous and stiff, you will fall. You’re too relaxed, you will also fall. To tread the middle way is being aware  of how our harsh world can hurt us but also how our heart can generate compassion and love, for ourselves as well as for all others.

Be patient and kind to ourselves. This will make our mind more malleable, we won’t get stuck within our own limitations. We won’t be judgmental of others’. Consequently the door to our heart will open wider. The mind is just a manifestation of our brain. The brain is that material property similar to our muscles. It can be developed into something pleasant or unpleasant for us. 

How much time and effort and dedication must an athlete devote to his sport to be of professional material? How much time should we devote to the training of our mind to reach that simple balance when facing the ups and downs of our daily life. Let’s not kid ourselves. Listen to the ‘how to’, understand it, like it…now apply it. Without the insight that arises from our own experience, within our own body and mind, all good information are just that, good information.

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
Basically, his technique is something like this:

1. Disconnect from your world (Sit comfortably & quiet, stay away from phones and any other distractions)
2. Be present (close your eyes, breathe slowly, and become nobody; forget about your past and don't try to predict the future)
3. Create your future self (Visualize who you want to become and let that be your identity - now!)
4. Rehearse the new you mentally (Think in detail about who you want to be and picture what will happen for your ideal self)
5. Let go of your past self and actualize the ideal self - keep practicing the new self and this meditation, until it becomes second nature.
Expect nothing - just practice.

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text: Wow! I am a Virgin Meditator and after watching this episode I committed to doing a mediation for longer than I would normally try. The bit in the episode that resonated with me, was Joe saying that everyone struggles to begin with, with all the noise in your head, but to just keep going until it settles down. I did this and I actually reached a point where I knew I was led there, but I wasn’t conscious of or thinking about anything at all. It felt euphoric (I know that sounds cliche) but it really did feel that way to me. After about 40 mins of being in this relaxed state, the headache that I had before I started the meditation, had completely gone. I’m extremely intrigued and excited to learn more about Joe Dispenza and his work. Isn’t it exciting to believe that there is something else! Something additional to ‘Matter’. Something other than 3 dimensional things in life. I want some of that! Great episode. Respectfully Steven, I detect that although you can see the benefits that your Partner experiences, my intuition tells me that it’s not something you see yourself doing at the moment, and I’m intrigued as to the reason why? It must be extremely difficult for you…your head must be full of so much noise from all the experts, Gurus etc, etc…how do you decipher who to listen and channel into? 🩵

comment_text:
# Dr. Joe Dispenza: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Key Insights

Dr. Joe Dispenza’s conversation offers a transformative perspective on how the mind can heal itself and help individuals live without fear and anxiety. Drawing from neuroscience, biology, and quantum physics, Dispenza provides practical insights into rewiring the mind, breaking free from emotional addictions, and creating a fulfilling life. Below are the comprehensive, in-depth key insights derived from his discussion, followed by a conclusion.

---

## 1. Emotional Stress Significantly Impacts Health
- **Core Idea**: Between 75% and 90% of healthcare visits in the Western world stem from emotional or psychological stress, highlighting its pervasive role in physical disease.
- **Explanation**: Dispenza explains that prolonged stress keeps the body in a survival mode, driven by stress hormones like cortisol and adrenaline. This "emergency mode" is unsustainable, weakening the immune system and leading to conditions such as chronic illness. People can even become addicted to these stress hormones, subconsciously seeking negative stimuli to maintain this heightened emotional state.
- **Implication**: Addressing emotional stress is critical for health, and Dispenza’s approach—using tools like meditation—offers a more effective alternative to pharmaceutical interventions, as supported by his research data.

---

## 2. Rewiring the Mind Enables Life-Changing Transformation
- **Core Idea**: By changing thoughts and emotions, individuals can rewire their minds and create lasting positive changes in their lives.
- **Explanation**: Dispenza teaches that neuroplasticity—the brain’s ability to reorganize itself—combined with intentional shifts in emotional states, allows people to break free from limiting patterns. His methods involve teaching neuroscience and biology in an accessible way, empowering individuals to understand and apply these principles for measurable outcomes like improved health or personal growth.
- **Implication**: This insight underscores the power of self-directed change, supported by scientific evidence from collaborations with institutions like UC San Diego and Harvard, showing biological shifts during meditation practices.

---

## 3. The Past Does Not Define You
- **Core Idea**: Individuals can transcend their past by choosing to learn and change in a state of joy, rather than waiting for pain to force transformation.
- **Explanation**: Dispenza challenges the notion that past experiences dictate identity, noting that 50% of personal narratives about the past may be inaccurate. He advocates for adopting new beliefs and emotions—such as inspiration and gratitude—within the same environment, enabling people to redefine themselves without external catalysts like trauma.
- **Implication**: This liberates individuals from being victims of their history, offering a proactive path to personal evolution rooted in positive emotional states.

---

## 4. Awareness Is the First Step to Change
- **Core Idea**: Becoming conscious of unconscious habits, beliefs, and emotional patterns is essential for personal transformation.
- **Explanation**: Dispenza emphasizes metacognition—the ability to observe oneself objectively—as a foundational step. Many behaviors are hardwired by midlife (95% of attitudes and perceptions), often programmed in childhood when the brain is highly suggestible. Meditation enhances present-moment awareness, allowing individuals to identify and overcome these automatic responses.
- **Implication**: Without awareness, people remain trapped in cycles of reactivity; cultivating it through practice opens the door to intentional change.

---

## 5. Meditation Unlocks Pure Consciousness and Healing
- **Core Idea**: Meditation settles the mind and body, enabling access to a state of pure consciousness that fosters healing and transformation.
- **Explanation**: The meditation process involves moving beyond the body, environment, and time, reducing brain waves from high-beta (stress) to coherent alpha or theta states (relaxation and suggestibility). This coherence synchronizes the brain and heart, enhancing creativity and emotional regulation. Dispenza’s research shows this state can upregulate genes and produce proteins that boost immunity, as seen in studies where IGA levels increased by 50% after three days of elevated emotions.
- **Implication**: Meditation is a practical tool to escape survival mode, heal the body, and create a new reality from a place of wholeness.

---

## 6. Forgiveness Frees You from the Past
- **Core Idea**: Forgiveness releases negative emotions, allowing individuals to reclaim energy for healing and growth.
- **Explanation**: Holding onto resentment or anger ties one’s identity to past events, perpetuating stress. Dispenza teaches that cultivating elevated emotions like love and gratitude triggers the release of chemicals like oxytocin, opening the heart and signaling the brain that the trauma is over. This process turns memories into wisdom, devoid of emotional charge.
- **Implication**: Forgiveness is not about excusing others but about self-liberation, a natural byproduct of shifting emotional states through meditation.

---

## 7. Brain-Heart Coherence Enhances Well-Being
- **Core Idea**: Synchronizing the brain and heart creates a coherent state that promotes relaxation, creativity, and overall health.
- **Explanation**: When the heart beats coherently (e.g., during meditation), it informs the brain to shift from stress-driven beta waves to alpha or gamma waves, associated with imagination and superconsciousness. This resonance boosts autonomic nervous system regulation, reducing stress and enhancing biological functions like immunity and neurogenesis.
- **Implication**: This connection illustrates how emotional regulation directly influences physical and mental well-being, offering a scientific basis for mind-body healing.

---

## 8. The Quantum Field: Creating from Wholeness
- **Core Idea**: By connecting to the quantum field—an invisible realm of energy and information—individuals can create their reality from a state of wholeness rather than lack.
- **Explanation**: Dispenza describes the quantum field as a unified energy beyond the material world, accessible in the present moment when one becomes "nobody, nowhere, no time." Coherent thoughts (electrical charge) and feelings (magnetic charge) broadcast intentions into this field, drawing experiences like synchronicities without physical effort. This contrasts with Newtonian, matter-based creation driven by lack.
- **Implication**: This paradigm shift encourages creating from abundance, fundamentally altering how goals are pursued and achieved.

---

## Conclusion
Dr. Joe Dispenza’s work unveils a profound truth: the mind holds the key to living without fear and anxiety by harnessing its innate capacity to heal and transform. His insights—rooted in science and practical application—reveal that emotional stress undermines health, but through awareness, meditation, and emotional regulation, individuals can rewire their minds and bodies. By releasing the past, fostering brain-heart coherence, and tapping into the quantum field, people can create a life of joy, health, and wholeness. Dispenza’s approach empowers individuals to take responsibility for their well-being, proving that personal transformation is not only possible but accessible to all who embrace these principles. This holistic framework offers a roadmap to a liberated, fulfilling existence, free from the shackles of fear and anxiety.

comment_text:
I’ve been doing a little thought experiment in response to this comment and thought you guys might be interested in a condensed version of my notes.

I think Joe Dispenza’s work and biblical teachings actually have a lot more in common than people usually realize.

Both focus on the idea that healing and transformation start inside of you — through your emotional state, your focus, and your faith in a future reality you can’t see yet.
Joe teaches that meditation lowers your brainwaves, connects you to the quantum field, and lets you reshape your mind and heart toward healing. You do this by consistently practicing elevated emotions like gratitude, love, and hope.
In a very similar way, the Bible teaches that transformation happens when you renew your mind, guard your heart, and walk by faith — trusting in unseen realities.

The biggest difference is relational.
Joe focuses on connecting with the “field” — an impersonal energy.
Jesus invites you to connect with God — a personal Being who loves you, heals you, and carries you even when you can’t carry yourself.
Just because someone accesses love or healing through the quantum field doesn’t mean they aren’t touching God’s reality — but they may miss the relationship and grace that come from knowing Him personally.

Another key difference is what happens after healing.
Joe’s model is mostly about personal change and achievement, even when shared with others.
In contrast, Jesus teaches that healing isn’t the end goal — it’s meant to overflow into service, compassion, and sacrificial love for others, especially the poor, the broken, and the outcast.

Some Bible verses that really show the connection:
	•	“Above all else, guard your heart, for everything you do flows from it.” (Proverbs 4:23)
	•	“Be transformed by the renewing of your mind.” (Romans 12:2)
	•	“Faith is the substance of things hoped for, the evidence of things not seen.” (Hebrews 11:1)
	•	“Enter his gates with thanksgiving and his courts with praise.” (Psalm 100:4)
	•	“If anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come.” (2 Corinthians 5:17)

Healing, transformation, and new life are real.
The invitation is even bigger, deeper, and more beautiful when you know the Healer personally.

comment_text:
i'm not sure this kind of thing can work long term-although there are some great insights
in psychotherapeutic/psychological terms its classic "Spiritual Bypassing"
over the years healers/teachers like Joe have come and gone
i get that folk have got a lot out of it in the short term and that's great...just wonder if its a band-aid/plaster for a few years but 5 /10 years down the line is when you really know if its worked


"Spiritual bypassing-using spiritual ideas & practices to sidestep personal, emotional 'unfinished business'- John Wellwood (Buddhist teacher and Psychotherapist) 

“when people have major spiritual openings ,often during periods of intensive practice or retreat, they imagine all has changed &they will never be the same again…at some point after the retreat ends, circumstances trigger their emotional reactivity, unresolved Psychological issues, habitual tensions/defences & subconscious identifications"

"For the most part psychological & spiritual work address different levels of human existence. Psychological inquiry(form) addresses relative truth,personal meaning-the human realm...The domain of Spiritual work is emptiness"

"Taking refuge in the impersonal absolute as a way to avoid dealing with one’s personal psychology, issues, feelings…leads to inner denial & this can lead to monstrous shadow elements devastating consequences"

"Spiritual bypassing often adopts a rationale based on using absolute truth to deny or disparage relative truth"

“spirituality becomes just another way of rejecting one’s experience…using spiritual practice to try to compensate for low self-esteem, social alienation or emotional problems, corrupts the true nature of spiritual practice”

"Most people in our culture who turn towards the spiritual life also suffer from psychological wounding, but their spiritual practice often does not address or help them understand or deal with their woundedness"



“the hard truth is that spiritual realization is relatively easy compared with the greater difficulty of actualizing it, integrating it fully into the fabric of ones embodiment/daily life”


"Spiritual involvement is particularly tricky for people who hide behind a narcissistic defence,because they use spirituality to make themselves feel special & important,while supposedly working on liberation from self"


-John Welwood (Toward a psychology of awakening )



In terms of a 'teacher/healer' that integrates the psychological domain and spiritual domain (both must be honoured) -not many better than Byron Katie

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
I always thought my mind just worked differently—like I was wired for overthinking and anxiety. I could be sitting in a quiet room, and my brain would still be running a hundred miles an hour. I avoided meditation for years because I assumed it wouldn’t work for me. Every time I tried, I got frustrated. My thoughts wouldn’t stop, and I’d give up after a few minutes.
A few months ago, a good friend recommended a book to me. She said it changed the way she saw her own mind, so I gave it a shot. It was Shift Your Mind by Alexander Brooks, and for the first time, meditation actually made sense to me. The book explained why my mind felt so chaotic and how I could step back from my thoughts instead of trying to control them.
I started doing the simple exercises from the book, just 10 minutes a day, and something shifted. My thoughts still came, but they didn’t have the same power over me anymore. If you’ve ever struggled with overthinking or feeling stuck in your head, I can’t recommend this book enough. It completely changed the way I approach stress and mindfulness. ❤

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
Ah, Joe Dispenza—the modern guru of the mind-body connection, the man blending neuroscience, quantum physics, and spirituality into one seductive cocktail. He’s a fascinating figure because he stands at the intersection of science and mysticism—a place where most thinkers either lose credibility or lose depth. But Dispenza? He’s managed to walk that thin line pretty successfully—at least in terms of attracting attention and building a movement.

Let’s break it down:

What He Gets Right

1. Mind and Body Connection
Dispenza’s core message—that your thoughts and emotions shape your physical and mental reality—is fundamentally true. Science backs it up: neuroplasticity (the brain’s ability to rewire itself), the placebo effect, and the impact of stress and emotions on physical health are all real phenomena. The idea that you can change your life by changing your thoughts and emotional states is not just spiritual fluff—it’s scientifically grounded.


2. The Power of Visualization
Dispenza teaches people to visualize their desired future with deep emotional intensity, and this is powerful. Athletes, performers, and even military personnel have used visualization techniques to enhance performance for decades. When you visualize something intensely, your brain starts wiring itself toward that reality. That’s not magic—it’s neuroscience.


3. Breaking Free from Conditioning
He emphasizes that most people live in repetitive emotional loops—anger, fear, anxiety—because their brain is wired for those patterns. This is true. The brain forms habits not just in action but in emotion and thought. Dispenza’s idea that you need to "rewire" the brain through focused intention and meditation is psychologically sound.


4. Meditation and Presence
Dispenza incorporates meditation as a key tool for transformation. That’s smart—because real transformation doesn’t come from thinking alone; it comes from silence, presence, and inner alignment. Meditation shifts brain waves, reduces stress, and creates space for higher cognitive and emotional states.




---

Where He Starts to Stretch Reality

1. Quantum Mysticism
Ah, the quantum card—this is where Dispenza walks a dangerous line. He often invokes quantum physics to explain how thoughts can directly influence physical reality. Now, quantum physics is real—but it operates at the subatomic level, not necessarily at the macro level of human experience. Saying that your thoughts can collapse quantum fields and directly alter physical matter without action—well, that’s where he slides into pseudoscience territory.


2. The Law of Attraction Trap
Dispenza flirts dangerously close to "law of attraction" thinking—the idea that you can manifest anything by thought alone. While thoughts absolutely influence behavior, motivation, and perception, sitting on your couch and "thinking rich" isn’t going to put money in your bank account. Visualization can prime you for action—but action is still required. Dispenza sometimes makes it sound like the universe will do all the work for you if you just vibrate at the right frequency. That’s spiritual escapism disguised as empowerment.


3. Overpromising Health Miracles
He claims that people have healed from cancer, chronic illnesses, and even paralysis through his methods. While the placebo effect and the mind’s influence on the immune system are scientifically valid, promoting the idea that "mind alone" can cure major diseases can be dangerous. It gives false hope and might encourage people to avoid proper medical care. The mind is powerful, but it’s not a magic wand.




---

The Real Problem with Dispenza’s Approach

The core issue is that he sells transformation as a product. He packages his teachings into expensive retreats, exclusive seminars, and premium courses. This creates the impression that you need his specific method to transform—which is just another trap of the ego. True transformation doesn’t come from a method or a workshop—it comes from direct experience, inner stillness, and self-awareness. The idea that you need to "follow Dispenza’s program" creates dependence, not liberation.

Buddha sat under a tree and found enlightenment for free. Osho spoke for hours without charging ticket fees for "VIP access to awakening." Dispenza, on the other hand, has turned transformation into a business. That’s not necessarily wrong—but it’s important to see the game for what it is.


---

So, What’s the Takeaway?

✅ Dispenza’s insights into the mind-body connection are valuable.
✅ His teachings on meditation, visualization, and emotional rewiring are grounded in psychology and neuroscience.
✅ The core idea that your thoughts and emotions shape your reality is fundamentally true.

❌ The quantum mysticism and "manifestation without action" claims are slippery and misleading.
❌ Healing serious diseases through thought alone—highly questionable and potentially dangerous.
❌ Transformation packaged as a high-priced product creates dependence, not true freedom.


---

How to Use Dispenza’s Teachings Without Getting Trapped

Use his teachings on meditation and visualization—they work.

Focus on changing emotional states, but don’t expect the universe to "deliver" success without action.

Take the mind-body connection seriously—but don’t expect miracles.

Be inspired by his ideas—but don’t turn him into a guru.

Remember: Transformation is not for sale. You already have everything you need within you.



---

Final Word:

Dispenza is not a fraud—he’s just a smart businessman with a mix of real wisdom and seductive fluff. Take the wisdom; leave the fluff. Don’t get lost in the quantum magic show—because real magic happens when you stop chasing and start being.

comment_text:
Great interview!

Re tuning into your own thought patterns and habits, I found the following from Shinzen Young useful. Notice (without judgement):

‘Talk activity’ (your voice and other’s voices)
Any images which are occurring.
Bodily sensations linked to thoughts. 

Try to categorise them e.g Is it a daydream / fantasy,  a memory, a judgement, a desire, problem solving, rehearsing etc

It does feel like extra effort to begin with, but by practicing this,  you create some distance from your own thoughts. I also found that I was able to quieten my mind much more easily and therefore be in the present moment. You notice how much nonsense goes on in your head and find it easier to get out of repetitive thought loops!

I’m currently going through Joe’s progressive online course for a second time and I’ve got a notebook I’m adding to constantly. His documentary Source It’s Within You is mind blowing!

comment_text:
Dr Joe is the physicist of spirituality. He explains, on a biological level, how our thoughts create our reality. These concepts have been known to humanity for thousands of years. However, he makes these truths more available to broader public by speaking modern language of scientific research and proof.

In the past, with very few distractions, people spend countless hours thinking and contemplating. There was just not that much to do. They found out these deep spiritual truths simply by practising awareness. Nowadays we need to stop our busy lives to become aware. We call it meditation. 

Although Dr Joe's reasearch makes it easier to understand the process and motivates you to make progress, it is not necessary. You don't need to know how a car works to drive it. In the same way you don't need to know the mechanics of meditation and prayer to transform your life. 

Dr Joe has always been an inspiration for my own change. His work is amazing. It helps a lot. However, there is more. There is a reason why we are here. We are one god learning about ourself by experiencing this reality we created on our own. When you find it out, it makes you even more powerful in shaping your reality the way you desire and achieving your goals. I wish you all the best in bringing love to your life and understanding what love is.

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
For people working through layers of trauma from child abuse, war zones, and other severe transgressions, please know that forgiveness is not a prerequisite for healing. As Judith Herman pointed out in her book Trauma & Recovery, she coined the term complex trauma 30 years ago. I understand the theory, which is rooted in religious and spiritual terminology.

When doing healing work, we cannot bypass what we had to dissociate from as children or in war zones, nor can we afford to zone out further. Healthy anger has fueled some of the greatest writers, artists, and musicians, leading to profound change on Earth and the creation of beauty.

Judith Herman explains:

"Revolted by the fantasy of revenge, some survivors attempt to bypass their outrage altogether through a fantasy of forgiveness. This fantasy, like its polar opposite, is an attempt at empowerment. The survivor imagines that she can transcend her rage and erase the impact of the trauma through a willed, defiant act of love. But it is not possible to exorcise the trauma through either hatred or love. Like revenge, the fantasy of forgiveness often becomes a cruel torture because it remains out of reach for most ordinary human beings.

Folk wisdom recognizes that to forgive is divine. And even divine forgiveness, in most religious systems, is not unconditional. True forgiveness cannot be granted until the perpetrator has sought and earned it through confession, repentance, and restitution.

"Genuine contrition in a perpetrator is a rare miracle. Fortunately, the survivor does not need to wait for it. Her healing depends on the discovery of restorative love in her own life; it does not require that this love be extended to the perpetrator. Once the survivor has mourned the traumatic event, she may be surprised to discover how uninteresting the perpetrator has become to her and how little concern she feels for his fate."

(Judith Herman, Trauma & Recovery, Pages 189-190, Chapter 9, "Remembrance and Mourning")

This passage serves as an important reminder that healing is a personal journey—one that does not demand forgiveness as a requirement.

For anyone who wants to learn meditation from a Buddhist perspective, this is a sutra that has been used since the creation of Buddhism.
 
1. ‘Breathing in a long breath, I know I am breathing in a long breath.
    Breathing out a long breath, I know I am breathing out a long breath.

    
2. Breathing in a short breath, I know I am breathing in a short breath.
    Breathing out a short breath, I know I am breathing out a short breath.
  
3. Breathing in, I am aware of my whole body.
    Breathing out, I am aware of my whole body.’
    He or she practices like this.


4.  Breathing in, I calm my whole body.
    Breathing out, I calm my whole body.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
5.  Breathing in, I feel joyful.
    Breathing out, I feel joyful.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
6. Breathing in, I feel happy.
    Breathing out, I feel happy.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
7. Breathing in, I am aware of my mental formations.
    Breathing out, I am aware of my mental formations.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
8.  Breathing in, I calm my mental formations.
    Breathing out, I calm my mental formations.’
    He or she practices like this.

9. Breathing in, I am aware of my mind.
    Breathing out, I am aware of my mind.’
    He or she practices like this.

10. Breathing in, I make my mind happy.
    Breathing out, I make my mind happy.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
11.Breathing in, I concentrate my mind.
    Breathing out, I concentrate my mind.’
    He or she practices like this.
   
12.Breathing in, I liberate my mind.
    Breathing out, I liberate my mind.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
 13. Breathing in, I observe the impermanent nature of all dharmas.
    Breathing out, I observe the impermanent nature of all dharmas.’
    He or she practices like this.
    
14. Breathing in, I observe the disappearance of desire.
    Breathing out, I observe the disappearance of desire.’
    He or she practices like this.
   
15.Breathing in, I observe the no-birth, no-death nature of all phenomena.
    Breathing out, I observe the no-birth, no-death nature of all phenomena.’ He or she practices like this.
   
16. Breathing in, I observe letting go.
    Breathing out, I observe letting go.’
    He or she practices like this.

The Full Awareness of Breathing, if developed and practiced continuously according to these instructions, will be rewarding and of great benefit. Edited by By Thich Nhat Hanh

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
The criticism against Joe Dispenza outweighs the proven scientific evidence supporting his ideas. While he incorporates legitimate neuroscience concepts, many of his claims—especially about healing diseases through thought alone and influencing reality with the mind—lack strong empirical support.

Key Criticisms Against Him
	1.	Lack of Scientific Studies – His ideas are based on neuroscience concepts but often lack peer-reviewed research backing his specific claims.
	2.	Misuse of Quantum Physics – He suggests that thoughts can directly affect reality at a quantum level, a claim that mainstream physicists do not support in the way he presents it.
	3.	Extraordinary Claims Without Extraordinary Evidence – He discusses spontaneous healings, radical life transformations, and mystical experiences but provides mostly anecdotal evidence rather than rigorous scientific proof.
	4.	Commercialization – His seminars, books, and courses are expensive, leading some to see him as more of a self-help entrepreneur than a serious scientist.

What Does Support His Ideas?
	•	Neuroplasticity: The brain can rewire itself based on thoughts and experiences, which is a well-established concept in neuroscience.
	•	Mind-Body Connection: Stress, meditation, and beliefs do influence health (e.g., the placebo effect is real, but its limits are still debated).
	•	Meditation Benefits: His meditation techniques can improve focus, reduce stress, and enhance well-being—effects supported by neuroscience, but not necessarily to the extent he claims.

Verdict

While some of what he teaches aligns with real neuroscience, he exaggerates the implications and mixes science with pseudoscience. If you’re interested in self-improvement and meditation, his work can be inspiring, but if you’re looking for solid scientific backing, his claims should be taken with skepticism.

Would you like recommendations for alternative sources with stronger scientific foundations?

comment_text:
So thankful to Dr. Joe Dispenza who helped me realize the roots of the intrusive negative thoughts I would suddenly get, even when all was going well in my life! 

My brain was (and still is to an extent) addicted to the chemicals generated by the negative experiences. If there were no negative experiences (i.e. my life was going well), my brain generated the negative thoughts which are perceived by the body as an actual occuring experience, causing the body to generate those chemicals. 

The brain "gets a hit" of those favorite chemicals and I feel like a pc of sh!t. Rinse and repeat into perpetuity. 

Thanks to Dr. Joe's work, I am in a much much better place. Even just seeing this cycle as an outside spectator, breaks the dark spell all of a sudden. 


Thank you, Dr. Joe!

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text: Steven you missed something in your understanding of how your parents affected you, and how that has gone on to affect your relationships. You heard your mum shout, this is boundaryless definitely. However, your dad was walled off. Walling off is just as damaging as boundarylessness. My guess would be you will work hard in your relationship to be right and probably have great difficulty in not quickly judging your partner to be 'too much; overbearing; overwhelming; wanting too much; etc. You most likely use what you believe to be implacable logic to 'prove' you are right. You will probably be confused about why partners you have had feel they are invisible. (you just want them to not need you and be independent). As a therapist i do not believe in wallowing in childhood ills for the very reason Mr Dispensa states, however, it can be very important to understand how you adapted to the experience of your parents with a mind that was a child's mind. It is that child's mind logic that rises up to protect you in your relationships in adult life. Unfortunately having your relationships run with the adaptations you made as a child does not lead to a healthy relationship. Your own walling off is likely to trigger a partner into getting to the point of shouting in an attempt to have some authentic connection. You are clearly an intelligent and thoughtful person so i imagine this is not what you would like to achieve from a relationship. Let me know if you want to know more about relationality in your relationship.

I know for me if someone had helped me change my life completely I would be writing how he did so and what change I needed, how long it took, if is it lasting change or a placebo effect, and if it could help people with severe mental conditions that may be contrbiutely hereditary-based, situation, or enviometally such as severe clinical depression, bi-polar personaty disorder, clinical anxiety including social phobia, OCD, ADHD, PTSD, borderline personality dsiorder, and alcohol and drug dependency. As someone who has dealt with some of the disorders mentioned previously and who has lost two siblings to suicide, I would be very interested in if anybody commenting on this video had been considerably helped with any of the previously mentioned disorders or has had a similar situation to mine. I am talking about profound help with serious mental conditions and how they profoundly interfere with an individual's life and not necessarily how he helped you quit smoking or stop sugar. Some great words of wisdom, which are very practical too.  Thank you for sharing!

Similarly, I think our past is a good place to learn from and self reflection can help us to see things from a more empathetic point of view. This takes a lot of courage, but it is definitely worth it because it helps us to identify the real root cause of our worry, fear or anxiety. Crazy how people still think Joe Dispenza is a real scientist — when he's actually just a chiropractor! 

He holds a Doctor of Chiropractic degree from Life University, a school focused on chiropractic, not neuroscience or physics. 

Yet he constantly talks like he's an expert in brain science and quantum physics, using fancy words to sell pseudoscience. If you check out "The Rise of Fake Scientists" on Ness Labs, it breaks down exactly how people like him twist scientific language to sound legit.

Yes, he studied biochemistry at Rutgers and holds a B.S. degree with an emphasis in neuroscience, but again, his doctorate is in chiropractic from Life University — a school focused on spinal adjustments, not brain science. 

Sure, being present and mindful is real, but he twists everything to his benefit. Cult leader I would say.

At the end of the day, he's a great marketer — but definitely not a scientist. Total fraud when you look at his actual credentials.

video_title: Secret To Living Without Fear & Anxiety Forever! Your Mind Can Heal Itself! - Dr. Joe Dispenza
comment_text:
@ I think despite our disagreements, our concept of consciousness may be quite similar. Personally I’m not convinced of a soul, though it doesn’t matter too much either way. My suspicions are that we are all fractals of oneness. That when we die we return to that oneness and re-emerge; not as the same ‘soul’, but rather another manifestation of universal consciousness.

However I’m always open to a more convincing theory. As I’m sure you’re aware, humans believe in all kinds of incorrect and silly things, because either we’re not as smart as we think we are, or due to cultural influence, or a desire for certainly, security, and to feel good about ourselves. The most reliable path to truth is open minded critical analysis. 

It’s evident that even the primal intelligence that created our bodies is flawed, and the universal consciousness that created that is also flawed. It’s learning, evolving, and often makes mistakes, and evil is a byproduct of the instincts that it created. But both good and evil come from a state of mind, so it would seem that the consciousness you’re referring to is beyond good and evil, and beyond the concepts of perfection and imperfection. 

So I maintain that the idea that we’re all perfect is false since at the level you speak of ‘we’ and ‘perfect’ aren’t really applicable. If you went up to the worst criminal in prison and told him ‘you’re perfect’, most people would think you’re insane. Seems to me people like this idea because then they can feel good about themselves without putting in the effort, or to take comfort in a positive simplification of the concept of being.

But we can agree to disagree. All the best.

@@thriverprivate3383  you’re attached to your story by the sounds of it which is very normal and he is not taking shots at people for that. 
he just asks when does that end ... freedom from the bad feelings associated with trauma and remembering trauma lie beyond the story is the point he’s making & has worked with thousands of people with all kinds of trauma i’m sure even people with every kind of bad childhood experience.  
i have to agree that unpacking trauma and understanding it is important vs ignoring it because ignoring it just leaves one as reactive vs aware of how it informs our thoughts and feelings. once one has that understanding however it’s active work to integrate it and push forward through all the fear and self loathing that’s holding one back from connection & growth as a person and feeling at peace in ones own skin. it’s the easy path to dismiss what he says because he didn’t mention someone with the certain trauma story that you’re referring to but chances are he’s worked with all varieties of trauma survivors. 
speaking here as a survivor of r a p e and childhood s e x abuse 
but these facts no longer affect my feelings they are just things that happened in the distant past 🙏.
